3. Security Audit
SEC-01 — CRITICAL: No Active Route Protection on Dashboard
Severity: P0 Critical

Files: middleware.ts (deleted), proxy.ts

middleware.ts was deleted (confirmed by git status: D middleware.ts). In its place, proxy.ts exists at the root with this export:


export function proxy(request: NextRequest) { ... }
Next.js only recognizes a file named middleware.ts exporting a default function named middleware. The proxy.ts file is entirely inert — Next.js never calls it. Result: every dashboard route (/dashboard, /dashboard/tickets/[id], /dashboard/qr) is fully accessible by anyone without authentication.

The login flow correctly creates a cookie, but nothing on the server ever checks it before serving dashboard pages.

Suggested fix: Rename proxy.ts → middleware.ts and rename the export from proxy to middleware (default export). No logic changes needed — the auth logic is already correct.

SEC-02 — CRITICAL: Live Credentials Committed in .env.local
Severity: P0 Critical

Files: .env.local

.env.local contains real production secrets:

Live Supabase project URL and anon key
The actual dashboard demo password
A live Resend API key
The notification recipient email
.env.local should never be committed to git. If this repo has a remote, these credentials are fully exposed in git history. All secrets should be considered compromised and rotated.

Additionally there's a slug mismatch: NEXT_PUBLIC_DEMO_RESTAURANT_SLUG=goros-sushi-demo in the env file, but CLAUDE.md and app/page.tsx reference sol-smoke-kitchen as the demo restaurant.

Suggested fix: Rotate all secrets immediately. Add .env.local to .gitignore. Create a .env.example with placeholder values.

SEC-03 — HIGH: Cookie Value Stores the Actual Password
Severity: P1 High

Files: app/dashboard/actions.ts (lines 22–28)


cookieStore.set('tabletalk_demo_auth', expected, { ... })
The cookie value is set to expected — the actual plaintext password. Auth is verified by cookie.value !== expected. Anyone who can read the cookie (e.g., via browser devtools, a network intercept on non-HTTPS, or a log) now knows the password itself.

Suggested fix: Store a secure constant token string (e.g. 'authenticated') or a HMAC of the password rather than the password itself.

SEC-04 — HIGH: /api/notify is Fully Public
Severity: P1 High

Files: app/api/notify/route.ts

The notify endpoint has no authentication check. Any person or bot can POST to /api/notify with arbitrary content and trigger emails to NOTIFY_EMAIL via the connected Resend account. This enables:

Email spam / inbox flooding of the restaurant owner
Resend quota exhaustion
Potential Resend account suspension
Suggested fix: Verify the request originates from the same origin (check Origin/Referer header), or add a shared secret header, or move this call to a Server Action that runs server-side after the Supabase insert.

SEC-05 — HIGH: Ticket Detail Page Has No Auth Check
Severity: P1 High

Files: app/dashboard/tickets/[id]/page.tsx

This page is 'use client' and directly calls supabase.from('guest_issues').update(...) for status and notes. Since the middleware is broken (SEC-01), anyone can:

Navigate directly to /dashboard/tickets/{any-id}
View guest PII (customer name, email, message)
Update status and internal notes for any ticket
The id comes from useParams() with no authorization check against which restaurant this ticket belongs to.

Suggested fix: Fix middleware first (SEC-01). Additionally, add a server-side row-level ownership check or ensure Supabase RLS prevents cross-restaurant access.

SEC-06 — MEDIUM: No Input Validation on API Route
Severity: P2 Medium

Files: app/api/notify/route.ts (lines 34–41)

After parsing JSON, the route destructures fields directly with no type/schema validation:


const { restaurantName, issueType, priority, guestStatus, tableNumber, message } = body
If any field is missing or wrong type, the code continues and produces undefined values in the email. escapeHtml() is applied to string fields, which is correct for XSS, but there's no validation that body even has the expected shape.

Suggested fix: Add a lightweight schema check (zod or manual null checks) before using the values.

SEC-07 — MEDIUM: Guest Form Has No Server-Side Validation
Severity: P2 Medium

Files: app/r/[slug]/page.tsx (lines 62–113)

Submission validation is entirely client-side (!selectedType || !message.trim()). The Supabase insert is called directly from the browser. A malicious actor bypassing the UI can:

Insert garbage data (empty strings, invalid issue types, very long strings)
Insert thousands of fake tickets for any known restaurant_id
No rate limiting exists on either the form or the API route.

Suggested fix: Add a Server Action for issue submission so validation runs server-side. Consider Supabase RLS to enforce field constraints. Rate-limiting via Vercel middleware or a simple IP-based check.

SEC-08 — LOW: Supabase Anon Key Exposed Client-Side (By Design, but Verify RLS)
Severity: P2 Low (risk depends on Supabase RLS config)

Files: lib/supabase.ts

NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY is intentionally public. Security depends entirely on Supabase Row Level Security policies. If RLS is not correctly configured, the anon key allows reading/writing any table without auth. This can't be fully evaluated from the codebase alone.

Suggested fix: Verify Supabase RLS is enabled on restaurants and guest_issues. At minimum: guest_issues should allow anonymous INSERT but restrict SELECT/UPDATE to authenticated sessions or service role only.

SEC-09 — LOW: console.error Leaks Internal Details
Severity: P3 Low

Files: app/api/notify/route.ts (lines 104, 109, 111), app/r/[slug]/page.tsx (lines 107, 110)

Server-side console.error with Resend error objects and raw client-side errors could log sensitive details (API keys in error objects, stack traces) to Vercel logs, which may be accessible to multiple team members.

4. Technical Debt
TD-01 — mock-data.ts Is Misnamed
Severity: Low

Files: lib/mock-data.ts

Contains only TypeScript type definitions (Ticket, Priority, Status, GuestStatus) — no mock data whatsoever. The name suggests mock data that can be removed later; the types themselves are load-bearing and should be in a file like lib/types.ts.

TD-02 — resolvedToday Counts All-Time Resolved, Not Today's
Severity: Medium

Files: app/dashboard/DashboardClient.tsx (line 68)


const resolvedToday = tickets.filter((t) => t.status === 'Resolved')
The variable is named resolvedToday and displayed in a "Resolved" stat card, but it has no date filter — it counts every resolved ticket since the beginning of time. For a restaurant that's been open for weeks, this number becomes meaningless.

TD-03 — topResolvedType Logic Runs on Every Render
Severity: Low

Files: app/dashboard/DashboardClient.tsx (lines 73–81)

The reduce + sort + Object.entries chain runs on every render, including the 60-second tick re-renders. This is minor now, but should be a useMemo.

TD-04 — Closed Status Is a Dead-End
Severity: Medium

Files: lib/db.ts (line 54), app/dashboard/tickets/[id]/page.tsx (line 14)

STATUS_LABELS includes Closed, and the Supabase schema presumably supports it, but STATUS_STEPS in the ticket detail page is:


const STATUS_STEPS: Status[] = ['New', 'Seen', 'In Progress', 'Resolved']
There is no way to set or transition to Closed from the UI. If a ticket arrives with status closed from the DB, statusConfig('Closed') works, but the stepper silently ignores it (STATUS_STEPS.indexOf('Closed') returns -1, making currentStepIndex = -1). The timeline rendering would be incorrect.

TD-05 — Duplicate Header/Nav Markup Across Pages
Severity: Low

Files: app/dashboard/DashboardClient.tsx, app/dashboard/tickets/[id]/page.tsx, app/dashboard/qr/QRClient.tsx

The dark bg-[#07111F] header with the TableTalk branding and back-navigation is reimplemented in each dashboard page. If branding or nav links change, each file needs updating independently.

TD-06 — Hardcoded Color Values Throughout
Severity: Low

Files: Multiple

Colors like #07111F, #009B9A, #DDFBFA, #9EECEB are hardcoded inline in dozens of places across every component. Tailwind CSS 4 supports CSS custom properties for this pattern; these should be design tokens.

TD-07 — proxy.ts Is a Dead File
Severity: Medium

Files: proxy.ts

This file is not imported by anything, not registered as middleware, and serves no purpose in the current build. It's a source of confusion — it looks like middleware, it has middleware-style logic, but it does nothing.

TD-08 — No Pagination on Ticket List
Severity: Medium (scaling concern)

Files: app/dashboard/page.tsx (lines 27–32)


const { data: issues } = await supabase
  .from('guest_issues')
  .select('*')
  .eq('restaurant_id', restaurant.id)
  .order('created_at', { ascending: false })
No .limit() or .range(). At scale this fetches every ticket ever created for the restaurant. The Realtime subscription then tracks all of them in client memory.

TD-09 — supabase.ts Throws at Module Load
Severity: Low

Files: lib/supabase.ts (line 6)


if (!url || !key) throw new Error('[TableTalk] Missing Supabase environment variables')
This throw happens at module evaluation time. In certain deployment/CI contexts (e.g., running next build without env vars set, or next lint), this will crash the entire module graph rather than producing a meaningful build error.

TD-10 — shadcn Components Installed but Not Used in Main Flows
Severity: Low

Files: components/ui/

badge.tsx, card.tsx, input.tsx, label.tsx, separator.tsx, textarea.tsx, alert.tsx, button.tsx — all shadcn components are installed. The main dashboard and guest form use none of them — they use raw <button>, <input>, <textarea> elements with inline Tailwind. This creates two parallel UI systems with no consistency guarantee.

5. UX / Product Issues
UX-01 — Dashboard Stat "Resolved" Is Misleading
Files: app/dashboard/DashboardClient.tsx

The "Resolved" count includes all-time resolved tickets (TD-02). A restaurant that opened yesterday and already resolved 50 tickets will show 50 forever, which conveys no operational signal.

UX-02 — No Status Filter or Search on Dashboard
Files: app/dashboard/DashboardClient.tsx

The ticket list shows all tickets, mixed status, in creation order only. As issues accumulate, staff can't filter to "New only" or "Critical" or search by table number. This is the primary operational screen.

UX-03 — No Pagination or "Load More" on Ticket List
Files: app/dashboard/page.tsx

Related to TD-08. The list has no visual end indicator, no page controls, and will grow indefinitely.

UX-04 — resetForm() Resets Guest Status to Default
Files: app/r/[slug]/page.tsx (line 123)


// setGuestStatus is NOT reset in resetForm()
Actually, resetForm() does NOT reset guestStatus to 'Still here' — but the initial useState default is 'Still here'. If a guest who already left submits and then hits "Submit another issue", the guestStatus retains their previous selection. This is technically correct behavior, but may not be intended.

UX-05 — Ticket Detail Page Has No Auth-Redirect UI
Files: app/dashboard/tickets/[id]/page.tsx

With the middleware broken (SEC-01), unauthenticated users land on the ticket detail with full access. Even when middleware is restored, the page itself has no fallback UI for "you aren't logged in" — it would just flash the Supabase data.

UX-06 — timeAgo() Has No Absolute Date Fallback
Files: lib/ticket-utils.ts (lines 22–31)

For tickets older than a few days, timeAgo() returns "3 days ago" with no hover tooltip or absolute timestamp. Staff reviewing old tickets can't tell the exact submission time.

UX-07 — Save Note Button Disabled When Notes Are Empty (Even for Clearing)
Files: app/dashboard/tickets/[id]/page.tsx (line 289)


disabled={!notes.trim() || notesSaving}
If a staff member wants to clear an existing note (delete its content), the button is disabled because !notes.trim() is true. They can't save an empty note to erase a previous one.

UX-08 — Copyright Year Is Stale
Files: app/page.tsx (line 148)


<p className="text-sm text-slate-400">© 2025 TableTalk</p>
Today is May 2026. The copyright year should be 2026 (or dynamic).

UX-09 — No Loading Skeleton on Dashboard
Files: app/dashboard/page.tsx

The dashboard is a Server Component that synchronously awaits two Supabase queries before returning HTML. During a slow network/DB response, the user sees a blank page with no loading indicator. There's no loading.tsx file in the dashboard segment.

UX-10 — Guest Form Has No Character Limit Hint on Message
Files: app/r/[slug]/page.tsx

The message textarea has no maxlength attribute and no character counter. If Supabase has a column length limit, a very long message will hit a DB error that surfaces as the generic "Something went wrong" message.

6. Production Readiness
PROD-01 — No loading.tsx or Suspense Boundaries
Severity: Medium

Next.js App Router supports loading.tsx files that show a skeleton during Server Component data fetching. None exist. The dashboard and QR pages do synchronous Supabase fetches with no loading fallback.

PROD-02 — No Error Boundary
Severity: Medium

No error.tsx files exist in any route segment. If a component throws during render (e.g., Supabase returns malformed data, dbToTicket receives unexpected shape), the error propagates to Next.js's default error page with no graceful recovery or friendly message.

PROD-03 — next.config.ts Is Empty
Severity: Low

Files: next.config.ts

No security headers (CSP, X-Frame-Options, X-Content-Type-Options), no image domain configuration, no redirect rules. For a production app serving a dashboard and public guest form, basic security headers should be set.

PROD-04 — RESEND_FROM_EMAIL Uses Sandbox Domain
Files: .env.local

RESEND_FROM_EMAIL=onboarding@resend.dev is Resend's shared sandbox domain, which has daily send limits and may have deliverability issues. Production needs a verified custom domain email.

PROD-05 — No Rate Limiting Anywhere
Severity: High

Guest form: unlimited inserts to guest_issues per IP
/api/notify: unlimited POST requests → unlimited emails
Login form: unlimited password attempts (brute-force possible)
No Vercel rate limiting, no middleware-based throttle, no Supabase rate limiting is configured in code.

PROD-06 — Env Slug Mismatch
Severity: Medium

NEXT_PUBLIC_DEMO_RESTAURANT_SLUG=goros-sushi-demo (env) vs. sol-smoke-kitchen (CLAUDE.md, hardcoded fallback in multiple files). The app will try to query a restaurant with slug goros-sushi-demo but the fallback in code is sol-smoke-kitchen. Whichever restaurant doesn't exist in Supabase will cause the dashboard to show the error state.

PROD-07 — No Monitoring or Alerting
Severity: Medium

No error tracking (Sentry, Axiom), no uptime monitoring, no structured logging. If the dashboard stops loading or emails stop sending, there's no automatic alert.

PROD-08 — resolvedToday Count Will Inflate Over Time (Vanity Metric)
Severity: Low

As noted in TD-02, the Resolved counter grows unbounded. For a restaurant in month 3, it could show "847 Resolved" which looks like a bug to staff.

